---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import TableOfContents from "../components/TableOfContents.astro";

// Define headings for table of contents
const headings = [
	// { depth: 2, slug: "intro", text: "1. Introduction" },
	{ depth: 2, slug: "about", text: "About Me" },
	{ depth: 2, slug: "experience", text: "Experience" },
	{ depth: 2, slug: "projects", text: "Projects" },
];
---

<Layout>
	<TableOfContents headings={headings} />
	<!-- Abstract / Intro -->
	<section id="intro" class="mb-12">
		<h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4 border-[var(--border-color)] pb-1">
			Hi, I'm Álvaro!
		</h1>
		<p class="text-justify">
        Incoming Master student in Mathematical and Theoretical Physics at
        the University of Oxford with
			experience in computational physics, machine learning, quantitative
			analysis, and complex systems.
			<!-- projects (<a
				href="#projects"
				class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)]">Projects</a
			>). -->
		</p>
        <!--		<p class="text-justify">
			You can find my CV here: <a
				href="/cv.pdf"
				class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)]">CV</a
			>.
		</p>
        --!>

	</section>

	<!-- About Section -->
	<section id="about" class="mb-12">
		<h2
			class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-1"
		>
			About Me
		</h2>

		<div class="mb-6">
			<p class="mb-4 text-justify">
            I enjoy using mathematical models to understand and predict
            complex problems. That interest led me to theoretical physics, where my
            studies at Trinity College Dublin developed my baseline in
            mathematical modelling and rigour, statistical reasoning, and stochastic
            methods for describing systems in which structure emerges from
            complexity.
			</p>
			<!-- <p class="mb-4 text-justify">
            I love building frameworks to solve problems. This lead me to 
            physics, which I studied intensely in my Bachelor's Degree in Theoretical
                Physics from Trinity College Dublin. In there, I studied the intricancies
                of the universe and its whims, developing a taste for the statistical and
                stochastic way to solve problems, and how order can appear from apparent
                chaos or complexity.
			</p> -->
			<p class="text-justify">
				My recent work involves theoretical physics and computation: building
				simulations, analysing high-dimensional data, testing numerical
                models, and using machine learning methods where they are useful. 
                
			</p>
		</div>

		<div class="mb-6">
			<h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-2">2.1. Technical Proficiency</h3>
			<p class="mb-2 italic opacity-90">
				The following technologies constitute my primary technical
				stack:
			</p>
			<div class="pl-4">
				<p>
                <span class="font-semibold">Languages:</span> Python,
			<a
				href="https://dreamsongs.com/WorseIsBetter.html"
				class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)]"
				>C++</a
			>

					HTML, CSS.
				</p>
				<p>
					<span class="font-semibold"
						>Frameworks &amp; Libraries:</span
					> NumPy, Matplotlib, Pandas, Polars, SciPy, Scikit-learn, numba,
					pytest, HOOMD, Optuna.
				</p>
				<p>
					<span class="font-semibold">Tools &amp; Environment:</span> Git,
					Docker, Pixi, Visual Studio Code, Vim, Linux, Windows,
					NixOS, ssh.
				</p>
				<p>
					<span class="font-semibold">Languages spoken:</span> Spanish,
					Catalan, English, German (Basic).
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- Experience Section -->
	<section id="experience" class="mb-12">
		<h2
			class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-1"
		>
			Experience
		</h2>
		<div class="flex justify-between gap-4 items-baseline mb-2">
			<h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-0">Alpha Options</h3>
            <span class="text-sm opacity-70 text-right whitespace-nowrap">May 2024-May 2025, May-Sept 2026</span>
		</div>
		<p class="mb-4 text-justify">
			Worked as a quantutative analyst in Barcelona. I developed random forest machine
			learning models for high-frequency market scenarios, focused on index
            fund options, obtaining alpha from mathematical methods and 
            technical intricancies.
		</p>
		<div class="flex justify-between gap-4 items-baseline mb-2">
			<h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-0">DAAD RISE Scholarship at SimTech, University of Stuttgart</h3>
			<span class="text-sm opacity-70 text-right whitespace-nowrap">May-Aug 2025</span>
		</div>
		<p class="mb-4 text-justify">
        Was a research intern in the SimTech cluster at the University of Stuttgart,
            working with Mario Gaimann and Miriam
            Klopotek on reservoir computing and active-matter simulations. Developed a 
            framework to test the robustness of active-matter as a source of predicting
            power in a reservoir computer.
		</p>
    </section>

	<section id="experience" class="mb-12">
		<h2
			class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-1"
		>
			Education
		</h2>

		<div class="flex justify-between gap-4 items-baseline mb-2">
			<h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-0">University of Oxford</h3>
			<span class="text-sm opacity-70 text-right whitespace-nowrap">2026-2027</span>
		</div>
		<p class="mb-4 text-justify">
            Incoming MSc in Mathematical and Theoretical Physics student.
		</p>
		<div class="flex justify-between gap-4 items-baseline mb-2">
			<h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-0">Trinity College Dublin</h3>
			<span class="text-sm opacity-70 text-right whitespace-nowrap">2022-2026</span>
		</div>
		<p class="mb-4 text-justify">
			B.A. Hons. Theoretical Physics graduate with a First Class
			Honours degree. Awarded the Arthur Lyster Prize in 2023 for one of
            the best first-year results in Mathematics and Theoretical Physics. 
            Acted as a member of the committee of the 
			<a
				href="https://tpsa.ie/student"
				class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)]"
				>Theoretical Physics Student Association</a
			>
            
            and the 
			<a
				href="https://trinityswimmingandwaterpolo.clubforce.com/"
				class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)]"
				>Dublin University Swimming Club</a
			>
            . Graduated with a First Class Honours.
            <!--, and the 
                Gold medal for outstanding performance on the degree overall. --!>
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Projects Section -->
	<section id="projects" class="mb-12">
		<h2
			class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-1"
		>
			Projects
		</h2>
		<h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-2">
			<a
				href="/projects/xy-model-lattice/"
				class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)]"
				>Characterising the XY Model on the Lattice</a
			>
		</h3>
		<p class="mb-4 text-justify">
			This was my final-year capstone project at Trinity College Dublin under
			Prof. Patrick Fritzsch. I computationally modelled the XY model on 2D
			and 3D lattices in C++ using Monte Carlo methods to extract critical exponents, study finite-size
			effects, and analyse its phase transition.
		</p>
		<h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-2">
			<a
                    href="/projects/reservoir-computing/"
				class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)]"
				>Reservoir Computing with Active Matter</a
			>
		</h3>
		<p class="mb-4 text-justify">
			Research carried out at the Stuttgart Center for Simulation Science
			(SimTech) through a DAAD RISE Scholarship. The project studies
			non-physical delayed-input reservoir computing against physical
			active-matter response, using Python, HOOMD simulations, and pytest
			verification.
		</p>
	</section>
</Layout>
